# Understanding req.body

The controller was updated:

```javascript
const createProduct = (req, res) => {
    console.log(req.body);

    res.json({
        message: "Product created successfully!",
        product: req.body,
    });
};
```

`req.body` contains the data sent by the client.

Example request from Postman:

```json
{
    "name": "Shampoo",
    "price": 850,
    "category": "Hair Care"
}
```

Inside the controller:

```javascript
req.body
```

became:

```javascript
{
    name: "Shampoo",
    price: 850,
    category: "Hair Care"
}
```

The response returned the same object back to Postman, confirming that the backend had successfully received the data.

---

# Request vs Response

One of the most important concepts learned during this session was the difference between requests and responses.

| Express Object | Purpose                                |
| -------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| `req.body`     | Receives incoming data from the client |
| `res.json()`   | Sends data back to the client          |

A simple way to remember this is:

```text
Request → Comes IN

Response → Goes OUT
```

